revision.text:
{{Year in Sri Lanka|1996}}

The following lists events that happened during '''[[1996]] in [[Sri Lanka]]'''.

==Incumbents==
*[[President of Sri Lanka|President]]: [[Chandrika Kumaratunga]] 

==Events==
* Sri Lanka wins the 1996 [[Cricket World Cup]] beating [[Australia]] by 7 wickets, making this Sri Lanka's first ever world cup win to date.<ref name="icc">{{cite web | url=http://www.espncricinfo.com/ci/engine/current/match/65192.html | title=Wills World Cup, Final: Australia v Sri Lanka at Lahore, Mar 17, 1996 Scorecard | publisher=ESPN | date=17 March 1996 | accessdate=12 August 2015}}</ref>
* The [[LTTE]] unleashes Operation Unceasing Waves, following a series of losses in the [[Jaffna Peninsula]], the Liberation Tigers of Tamil Elam, launch an attack on [[Battle of Mullaitivu (1996)|Mullaitivu]]. The [[Sri Lankan Army]] is defeated leaving 1,242 SLA soldiers dead, and hundreds captured and executed.  <ref name="SR">[http://sundaytimes.lk/961013/sitrep.html Situation Report, By Iqbal Athas]</ref> It has also been reported that others were found dead clutching white flags of surrender.<ref>[http://www.crimesofwar.org/thebook/quarter-giving-no.html Quarter, Giving No By John Burns] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081231051315/http://www.crimesofwar.org/thebook/quarter-giving-no.html |date=2008-12-31 }}</ref>
* On July 24, 1996, a train is bombed in Dehiwala, killing 42 and wounding 400. The LTTE was claimed responsible for the attack, placing suitcase bombs in four carriages on a commuter train. <ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1996/09/04/world/tamil-arrested-in-sri-lanka-train-bombing.html|title=Tamil Arrested in Sri Lanka Train Bombing|work=The New York Times|date=1996-09-04}}</ref>
