{{Short description|American painter}} {{more footnotes|date=June 2013}} [[File:Driskell Woman with Flowers.jpg|thumbnail|Woman with Flowers by David Driskell, 1972]] [[File:50th-Loh-Driskell-Henney.jpg|thumbnail|The [[University of Maryland, College Park]] Art Gallery celebrated its 50th anniversary on Feb. 24, 2016 with a memorable art exhibition. Among those attending were President [[Wallace Loh]] and his wife, Barbara, on the left; and Prof. David C. Driskell, along with Prof. [[Dagmar R. Henney]], on the right. Photo courtesy University of Maryland Art Gallery, used with permission.]] '''David C. Driskell''' (born June 7, 1931 in [[Eatonton, Georgia]])<ref name=HistoryMakers>{{cite web|title=ArtMakers : David Driskell|url=http://www.thehistorymakers.com/biography/david-driskell-40|website=The History Makers|accessdate=December 4, 2015}}</ref> is an [[artist]] and a scholar in the field of [[African-American art]]. Driskell is an [[Emeritus|emeritus professor]] at the [[University of Maryland, College Park]].
Driskell holds a Master of Fine Arts degree from [[The Catholic University of America|Catholic University]] and nine Honorary Doctoral degrees.<ref name="neh" /> In 2000, Driskell was honored by President [[Bill Clinton]] as one of 12 recipients of the [[National Humanities Medal]]. <ref name= "neh">{{cite web|title=AWARDS & HONORS: 2000 NATIONAL HUMANITIES MEDALIST: David C. Driskell|url=http://www.neh.gov/about/awards/national-humanities-medals/david-c-driskell|publisher=National Endowment for the Humanities|accessdate=July 19, 2013}}</ref> ''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar'' by Julie L. McGee, a book detailing Driskell's life and work, was published in 2006.<ref>Julie L. McGee, [https://www.amazon.com/David-C-Driskell-Artist-Scholar/dp/B00BDIO9OQ ''David C. Driskell: Artist and Scholar''], Pomegranate Communications, 2006, {{ISBN|0764937472}}.</ref>
Driskell is represented by DC Moore Gallery. His first exhibition at the gallery was held in October 2006.<ref name="DC Moore Gallery, artist page">{{cite web|title=DC Moore Gallery, artist page|url=http://www.dcmooregallery.com/artists/david-driskell|accessdate=February 1, 2013}}</ref>
==Publications by Driskell== * ''Amistad II: Afro-American Art'' (editor), Nashville: [[Fisk University]], 1975. * ''[[Two Centuries of Black American Art]]'', Los Angeles: [[Los Angeles County Museum of Art]], 1976. {{ISBN|0-87587-070-8}} * ''The Afro-American Collection, Fisk University'', with Earl J. Hooks, Nashville: [[Fisk University]], 1976. * '' Harlem Renaissance: Art of Black America'', introduction by Mary Schmidt Campbell; essays by David Driskell, David Levering Lewis, and [[Deborah Willis (artist)|Deborah Willis Ryan]], New York: [[The Studio Museum in Harlem]], 1987. {{ISBN|0-8109-1099-3}} * '' Introspectives: Contemporary Art by Americans and Brazilians of African descent'', curators, Henry J. Drewal and David C. Driskell, Los Angeles: [[California Afro-American Museum]], 1989. * ''African American Visual Aesthetics: a Postmodernist View'' (editor) Washington, D.C.: [[Smithsonian Institution|Smithsonian Institution Press]], 1995. {{ISBN|1-56098-605-0}} * ''The Other Side of Color: African American Art in the Collection of [[Camille Olivia Hanks-Cosby|Camille O.]] and [[William H. Cosby, Jr.]]'', San Francisco: Pomegranate, 2001. {{ISBN|0-7649-1455-3}}
